kstart#avoid-carrying-tuples-through-every-layer","content":"Avoid: carrying tuples through every layer"},"214":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#good-pass-cancellation-into-real-io","content":"Good: pass cancellation into real I/O"},"215":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-expecting-yieldless-to-stop-work-that-ignores-signals","content":"Avoid: expecting Yieldless to stop work that ignores signals"},"216":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"The fastest way to understand Yieldless is to wire the core pieces together:"},"217":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/error` to keep failures in tuple form"},"218":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/result` when tuple branches need light composition"},"219":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/task`, `yieldless/all`, and `yieldless/iterable` to fan work out and cancel siblings cleanly"},"220":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/retry`, `yieldless/signal`, and `yieldless/timer` for resilient async boundaries"},"221":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"Boundary adapters like `yieldless/fetch`, `yieldless/schema`, `yieldless/router`, `yieldless/ipc`, `yieldless/node`, and `yieldless/env`"},"222":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#install","content":"TypeScript 5.5+ is the target baseline. The package is compiled with `isolatedDeclarations` enabled."},"223":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"`safeTry()` and `safeTrySync()` let you treat common failures as data instead of exception control flow."},"224":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"That pattern is the center of the library. Every module is designed to fit back into the same `[error, value]` shape."},"225":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"When a tuple flow grows past one branch, use `yieldless/result` to keep it readable."},"226":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"Keep this modest. If one `if (error)` branch is clearer, use the branch."},"227":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"`runTaskGroup()` gives you a shared abort signal and sibling failure propagation."},"228":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"If `readRefs()` throws, the group aborts the shared signal, waits for `readStatus()` to settle, and then rethrows the original failure.\nIf the request or UI flow already has an `AbortSignal`, pass it in so the whole group inherits upstream cancellation."},"229":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"When the work is a list rather than a few named tasks, use `mapLimit()` to keep pressure on the outside world under control."},"230":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"The result order matches the input order, and the first tuple error aborts the remaining in-flight work."},"231":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"For async streams or generators, reach for `yieldless/iterable` instead of materializing everything first."},"232":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Retries should stay close to transport boundaries: HTTP, queues, database connections, and subprocesses that can legitimately fail for transient reasons."},"233":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"The retry loop respects `AbortSignal`, so if a parent task group is canceled, the pending backoff timer is canceled too."},"234":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"When a boundary needs a firm time budget, derive one signal and pass it through the whole call chain."},"235":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"If you are calling HTTP JSON APIs, `yieldless/fetch` combines the same ideas:"},"236":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"If you need to wait for eventual consistency, use `poll()` instead of hand-writing timers."},"237":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"The package ships adapters for common backend boundaries:"},"238":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/env` validates startup configuration"},"239":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/fetch` wraps HTTP status, JSON parsing, and deadlines"},"240":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/schema` keeps validators in tuple form"},"241":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/router` turns tuple handlers into HTTP responses"},"242":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/ipc` preserves tuple results across Electron IPC"},"243":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/node` wraps filesystem and child-process work"},"244":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/event` waits for one event with cleanup and abort support"},"245":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/singleflight` deduplicates duplicate in-flight work"},"246":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Module Selection when you are deciding which helper fits a specific problem."},"247":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Design Rules before you spread the tuple style across a large codebase."},"248":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Do and Don't if you are moving a team onto the library and want the conventions to stay sharp."},"249":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-46","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Use the reference section when you already know what module you need."},"250":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-47","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-carrying-tuples-through-every-layer","content":"Most UI and domain code wants ordinary values or ordinary state. Convert at the boundary."},"251":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"page","content":"Bounded Batch Work","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work"},"252":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Process lists of API, filesystem, or subprocess work without unbounded parallelism."},"253":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#refresh-several-repositories","content":"Refresh several repositories"},"254":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Why this is friendlier"},"255":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"Good variation: stream the input"},"256":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"Avoid: unbounded fan-out"},"257":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"This recipe is for the common \"do this for every item\" path: refresh every repo, fetch every avatar, resize every image, or inspect every file. The work is independent, but starting it all at once can make a user's machine or an upstream service miserable."},"258":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when you want tuple errors, shared cancellation, stable output order, and a hard ceiling on active work."},"259":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Output order matches `repositories`, so UI code does not need to sort the result back into place."},"260":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"The first tuple error aborts in-flight work and stops starting new items."},"261":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"A parent `AbortSignal` can cancel the whole batch when the user navigates away."},"262":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"`concurrency` is explicit, so expensive work stays polite by default."},"263":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"If repositories come from an async source, use `yieldless/iterable` instead of building a large array first."},"264":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"That can launch dozens or hundreds of subprocesses. Use `mapLimit()` or `mapAsyncLimit()` so the user’s machine stays responsive."},"265":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"page","content":"Electron Git Client","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client"},"266":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"An end-to-end shape for a desktop Git app using IPC tuples, abortable subprocesses, and typed renderer calls."},"267":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"268":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"269":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"270":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#renderer-usage","content":"Renderer usage"},"271":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Why this boundary feels cleaner"},"272":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"273":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"274":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"Yieldless 